### Description

It seams we cannot use the same name as a signal property like we does with `as` alias. This is a shame as it leads to the use of more verbose names like `@let userData = user()`.

The following code throw error `NG8016: Cannot read @let declaration 'user' before it has been defined.`

```html
@let user = user();
```

But this one works perfectly

```html
@if (user(); as user) {
  <!-- ... -->
}
```

### Proposed solution

```html
@let user = user()
```

or maybe simply infer signal extraction

```html
@let user;
```

### Alternatives considered

Any better idea ?

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Not sure if I missed something. When I have a signal inside my component and I want this to be exposed as output only - there is no way to archive this yet, right?

If I want to use it as both input and output, there is `model()`. But do we have an equivalent for outputs yet?

So currently I probably would do:

```typescript
import { outputFromObservable } from '@angular/core/rxjs-interop';
import { toObservable } from '@angular/core/rxjs-interop';

@Component({
  // ...
})
export class MyComponent {
  private count = signal(0);
  
  public readonly countChanged = outputFromObservable(toObservable(this.count));

  increment() {
    this.count.update(value => value + 1);
  }
}
```

### Proposed solution

What about simplifying this to:

```typescript
import { outputFromSignal } from '@angular/core/rxjs-interop';

@Component({
  // ...
})
export class MyComponent {
  private count = signal(0);
  
  public readonly countChanged = outputFromSignal(this.count);

  increment() {
    this.count.update(value => value + 1);
  }
}
```

And / or then also add `outputToSignal`.

To take this one step further: I would like to directly get a (read-only) signal inside a parent component that uses MyComponent.

Is it possible to bind an output (signal) directly to a signal of the parent?

### Alternatives considered

1. see above using `outputFromObservable(toObservable(this.count))`
2. `effect(() => { this.countChanged.emit(this.count()); });`

